        "text": "א",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", B, C, D, L, &c.). Nathanael had recognised Him as “the Son of God” and “the King of Israel.” Later, Martha confessed Him as “the Christ, the Son of God,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 11:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But now for the first time the revealed mystery was openly recognised and confessed. St Luke omits the blessing of St Peter, which whatever may be its exact meaning at any rate can have conferred on him no sort of primacy or superior authority among the Apostles. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:24-26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
